Node.Notes: Most see "deer/doe of the dawn/morning" as the name of the tune to which the psalm was sung.
Uncertain. Tree assumes "[why are you] far from saving me, [from] the words of my groaning?"
The way others view the psalmist, as scorned and despired by people indicates in the rest of the verse.
To make opening with the lip, figure for a gesture of derision/scorn.

Literally, "to roll," probably in sense of rolled cause/suffering onto, hence relied/trusted. Masoretic text has imperative mood, "Trust!." Most follow LXX and other ancient translations with different vowels to get indicative mood "he trusted."
Bashan was famous for its cattle. The strong bulls of Bashan metaphorically refer to the psalmist's enemies.
Lion is singular, open wide is plural, so "lion" not S. Tree assumes "They [i.e., the enemies] open wide their mouth against me; [they are like] a lion tearing prey and roaring."
Seems to be figure for complete exhaustion/utter weakness.
Apparently figure for complete lost of courage and hope.
A piece of broken clay jar, which is completely dry and brittle.
Though not dead yet (but brought to the brink of death), the psalmist felt as if God had already deposited him in death's dust (Sheol as a place of dust).
Uncertain. Many follow LXX (which is apparently cited by NT) and change the word to "they pierced." MT text might make sense as something like "like a lion [they mauled] my hands and my feet."
Together with the preposition B.: that follows,, to take a look at/fix one's gaze on, possibly to gloat.
Literally, "the only one," which in parallel with my soul/life, probably refers to the only life I will ever have/my precious life.

Uncertain. Many follow LXX and change "you answered me" slightly to "my oppressed self," with "deliver" from first half carried over. Some retain MT, but take "you answered me" in sense of "you defended/rescued me," which is probable.
